fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
First, we show that the subobject poset of P is a lattice.
  Let S and T be subfunctors of P. Then:

the meet is given by (P\wedge  Q)X = PX\cap  QX;

the join is given by (P\vee  Q)X = PX\cup  QX;

the implication is given by (P\Rightarrow  Q)X = \{x\in  PX: \text { for all }     Y\xrightarrow {f} X\in  C, \text { if } Pf(x)\in  SY \text { then } Pf(x)\in  TY\}.

The universal property of the coproduct P =   \coprod _{j\in  J} X_j with coprojections X_k\xrightarrow {\iota _k} P is that, for any
  object Z equipped with morphisms X_k\xrightarrow {\kappa _k} Z, there exists a unique
  morphism P\to  Z making the following diagrams commute:




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
      X_k\ar [r, "\iota _k"]\ar [dr, "\kappa _k"'] & P\ar [d, dashed, "\exists  !"] \\
      & Z\makebox [0pt][l]{.}
    \end {tikzcd}

When J is the ordinal category 2, hence the diagram is
  of shape \bullet \,\bullet , and so the coproduct is of two objects X and
  Y, this property has the following nice form:




